		<hr size="1">RE.. Wizard balance</P><P><BR>     	I've been reading the Boards trying to figure out what may help our class out. I believe Nanaeve comes the closest to what I beleive.		<BR>	First let me say that when I hear a Wizard shout "Looking for a group" I don't even want to group with him. I'm sorry to say I feel this way and I'm a Wizard myself. It's a shame I feel this way and is just plain not fair. I would group with any other class first. This is terrible.<BR>	When I'm in a group sitting and medding every other fight, I feel guilty taking experience. I'm sure the other members of the group feel the same way. I'm constantly mana managing and deciding if and when I should cast. I know the other group members see this and become to resent watching me medding while they are fighting. "Master of D&D" that seems funny at times when I'm low on mana, which is always in a group. I have been tempted many times to cast my level one spell  "They think I am helping" SO THEY KEEP ME IN THE GROUP, BECAUSE THEY WONT KNOW IF I HIT FOR 10 DAMAGE OR 500 DAMAGE ANYWAYS. At least it looks better than sitting there medding.<BR>	The solution I feel the most comfortable with, which has been suggested by others, is to give Wizards a mana regeneration bonus when grouped, per members in the group. It has been suggested anywhere's from 10% to 20% per person in the group for mana regeneration.<BR>	This would accomplish 2 things, #1 Would help with the fear VI has of a Wizard becoming a solo machine if they make spells more powerful. #2 It would make a Wizard in a group able to cast more than Once or twice in a fight and maybe actually do an even amount of damage to a mob as others in the group. I for one would become a searcher for groups, just for the extra mana regeneration. Wouldn't it be nice to see a Wizard actually casting in a group instead of holding back . The group would appreciate the extra casts also and maybe bring into line the "Master of D&D" so that a group may actually believe that a Wizard may come close to that truth.<BR><br>&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;<br></font>
	</font>
	</td>
